Ukraine on the Way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and they will never meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
The Ukraine is indeed in the East, but in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the prevailing goal for many of us.
The path there, however, was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It is beyond question for me that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties of Ukraine in finding accession to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The huge agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture according to the Soviet model.
The rural population was deeply mired in filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We messed up the reform all by ourselves.
Because often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has, over the years, adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
You can see that on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to take care of themselves against reckless drivers).
Now in Kyiv there is a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the net in internet cafes.
But these are just the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober look of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, a development has taken place ranging from total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
Initially, the reform of the state provoked a hostile mood both among bureaucrats and among ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "by-the-book" reform: the state had to shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better by simply cutting red tape led us to the second stage in our reform process.
The state was gradually reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
The work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At first, the powers delegated to these new areas were somewhat too extensive to make their work more effective.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (although reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians accept them as well.
Only radicals and populists - of which there are still too many among us - can afford to take an indifferent attitude toward a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the Tsarist Empire, the most important, but nevertheless a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a by-product of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial person cannot in any way admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to realize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have contributed to becoming even more sick, but the recently held elections, which have deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curbed the power of President Kuchma's "powerful parties," have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalized individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all nature's achievements, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous journey toward Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
